<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">Groups can get awfully creative with use of "tanks" in WoW.  That said, it's true that high end instances most definitely require healers.  Two of the last 3 non-raid instances currently in WoW also favor one particular healing class, the priest - due to their ability to shackle (mez) undead.
<br />

<br />
WoW does have its "holy trinity" as some players call it.  IMHO, it's more of a holy duo - Priest and Mage.  Priests are highly favored due to shackle undead (a priest-only ability), the most efficient quick heals (WoW is all about fast heals, and less about big, slow casting heals) while Mages are favored for AE damage and Humanoid mez.  Oh yeah, priests have a castable rune good for keeping mages alive.
<br />

<br />
True, a warrior or paladin will significantly reduce downtime compared to having a pet tank - but druids seem to be able to tank fairly well in bear form.  I don't know how viable paladins are at the high end, with respect to ability to get and maintain agro.  My group has relied on a shaman tank on more than one occasion in instances, although I don't know how well this would work in Stratholme or Scholomance.
<br />

<br />
As new content becomes available for WoW, we'll see if the holy trinity/duo perseveres.  My bet is it will.  Outside of instances (think LDoN in EQ - though in WoW it's where the best quests/drops take place), any group can defeat any encounter within appropriate level range.  That and any class to solo to max level.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
