Medal of Honor
<br />

<br />
Any number of 'rpg's out there that cover a wide range of classes wherein the situation is always doable no matter which class you choose...
<br />
/sarcasm off
<br />

<br />
Any game where each and every class can, essentially, solo will break down to being tantamount to a first person shooter... thus the sarcastic reply above.  With WoW, I felt like I was playing an unbalanced FPS, so, I quit.  Same goes for CoH.  Both games have one thread in common: they both tried to keep downtime minimized by ensuring that all classes could stand alone and that no single class was absolutely necessary.
<br />

<br />
Problem is, if no class is necessary, all classes have to be able to stand up on their own and you end up with a situation where you don't group as much as you otherwise would... even worse, you don't really have to develop any play skillls, as a group, since by definition grouping only makes the same content easier.  This is obvious when you compare WoW to EQ by watching how each class member acts in a group.  In EQ a healing class WILL heal or the group will eject the healer (assuming the healing class is fulfilling the role of primary healer) in WoW you will find primary healers who don't heal but rather tank a lot... and the group won't care because the group will get along fine, if a bit roughly, without a healer.
<br />

<br />
Sorry if this upsets anyone, I don't mean this as a slam to WoW or EQ (or any other game) but an observation of games where classes can stand alone and solo with impunity versus a game where classes have to work together to make progress... at least in limited cases (the whole game doesn't have to require grouping, but, some content will, is what I'm getting at).</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
